I. Introduction¶

This project aims to explore the works of social contract theorists Thomas Hobbes, Jean-Jacques Rousseau and John Locke in an effort to probe the unique tensions and nuances of their opposing positions. In order to contextualize the work presented, it is necessary to provide a brief summary of the discourse in question. While the motifs of social contract theory date back to the dialogues of Plato, the particular doctrine of which we speak rose to prominence in the middle of the 17$^{th}$ century and remained a hot-button philosophical issue until the mid-19$^{th}$ century (a careful observer may know this period as the Age of Enlightenment). In the most fundamental sense, social contract theory asks how the governing authority justifies its power over the ruled, how civilization comes to exist. It is generally accepted that, in any organized society, citizens must forfeit some degree of personal autonomy in exchange for order, harmony and security -- a mandate which stems from what social contract theorists term 'the state of nature' in reference to the most base condition of human behavior (DAgostino, 2021).


The shape of a given social contract theory is inherently dependent on the theorist's notion of human nature -- whether human beings are, at our cores, creatures of compassion and justice, or of violence and self-interest. The fate of the political body which successfully supports society depends on an accurate read of the motives and values underpinning human behavior. It is on this point, the essence of human nature, where Hobbes, Locke and Rousseau diverge. For Hobbes, human beings in their natural state (that is, without the imposition of civil authority) were fearful, self-interested, brutish creatures. It follows that, in Hobbes' understanding, society arises from mutual self-interest: a utilitarian truce rooted in a collective desire to preserve our own necks. Rousseau stands in stark opposition to Hobbes, suggesting that the state of nature (in his view, long left behind) was one of tranquility and equality. For Rousseau, the invention of property (the idea that an individual could claim an exclusive right to some finite resource) irrevocably banished this utopian existence. Rousseau's social contract is the modern attempt to artificially impose the blithe harmony of the past through mutual agreement and adherence to the will of the majority. Locke, on the other hand, occupies the liminal space between these two notions. Locke aligns with Rousseau in his conception of the state of nature, seeing it as dominated by peace and mutual assistance, but marks it ultimately as a bygone era. For Locke, the invention of property and the abandonment of our natural state made humans creatures governed mostly by fear, often resorting to violence to defend their claims and person. For this reason, Hobbes and Locke are often situated in opposition to Rousseau. (Laskar, 2013)


This work seeks to examine the debate between Hobbes, Rousseau and Locke, asking chiefly whether this commonly-accepted categorization of each theorist is truly born out in the text.

Table 2: description and location of analytical tables

First, the six texts included in this corpus were parsed and tokenized. Metadata regarding each text (including the number of chapters and tokens) was saved in a LIB table. The ordered hierarchy of content objects (OHCO) utilized in tokenization went: book, chapter, paragraph, sentence and token, in line with the pattern commonly used when analyzing novels. A complete table of tokens representing the contents of the corpus was saved as the CORPUS table. All numeric and symbolic terms were removed from the CORPUS. The VOCAB table was then generated by simply aggregating appearances of each unique token within the CORPUS. VOCAB was annotated with the probability that a given token would appear in the CORPUS (p), the entropy, or uncertainty surrounding the appearance of a term (h), the information content (i) which can be thought of as the degree of surprise associated with a term's appearance, the part of speech (max_pos) represented by each term, whether a term represented a stop word (stop), and several different methods of extracting the stem of each term. Before moving to more advanced exploratory techniques, the Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency (TF-IDF) and Document Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency (DF-IDF) were computed and appended to the CORPUS and VOCAB tables, respectively.

In the process of principal component analysis (PCA), the top 10 principal components were assessed, using chapter as the document level which allowed sufficient granularity within each work. The results of this work will be discussed in a later section, here we simply note the resulting LOADINGS and DCM tables, which contain the correlation coefficients between the terms and the top 10 principal components, and the weighted scores of each principal component in each document, respectively.

Latent dirichlet allocation (LDA), or topic modeling, produced the PHI (topic and term counts) and THETA (each row represents a document, each column a topic) tables which were combined to create the TOPICS table. Obtaining word embeddings yielded the W2V table, containing terms and their respective embeddings. Finally, sentiment analysis produced the SENTIMENT (aligns sentiment and emotion values as features in VOCAB) and DOC_EMO (shows the sentiment polarity and emotion by document) tables.

IV. Exploration¶

Principal Components (PCA)¶

Principal component analysis was useful in visualizing the ways in which Hobbes, Rousseau and Locke were positioned in relation to one another -- truly getting at the heart of this inquiry. For these purposes, it was worthwhile to examine the ways in which clusters appeared, both when grouping by author and by individual text. If there are indeed significant differences in each theorist's beliefs, any clusters apparent when grouping by author ougth to persist at the level of individual texts. Moreover, if the generally accepted divergence between the two schools of thought is to hold, Rousseaus' work should be markedly distinct from that of Hobbes and Locke, whose texts should exhibit significant overlap.

In [2]:
display(Image(filename='fig1.png'))

Figure 1: distribution of works of Hobbes, Rousseau and Locke (bagging by chapter) across principal components 0 and 1.

At first glance, the distribution of Hobbes, Rousseau and Locke's works appears misaligned with the scholarly consensus (Fig. 1). Most notable is the overlap between Rousseau and Locke, but it is important to bear in mind that these works span a vast array of questions, and alignment on one set of issues should not be overinterpreted.

In [3]:
display(Image(filename='fig2.png'))

Figure 2: distribution of works of Hobbes, Rousseau and Locke (bagging by chapter) across principal components 0 and 1

Hobbes and Rousseau seem more aligned with respect to PC0, which is positively associated with terms including 'government', 'commonwealth' and 'law'. In contrast, Locke's works seem evenly dispersed across PC0, with a notable cluster towards the negative values, associated with terms like 'idea', 'mind', and 'knowledge'. PC1 seems responsible for dividing Hobbes, Locke and Rousseau most dramatically, with the negative end of the span representing terms like 'government' and 'state' while the positive end includes 'god', 'kingdome' and 'christ' -- suggesting Hobbes perhaps more interested in engaging the idea of divine right than his counterparts.

It is important to mention that these plots were generated by first filtering the COURPUS such that only the top 1000 terms with a max_pos tag in the list 'NN', 'VB', 'JJ', in order to ensure imformative results. Works were bagged by chapter and covariance was computed off of L2 TFIDF.

Topic Models (LDA)¶

To further investigate the themes, arguments and convictions most important to each respective thinker, LDA was employed.

To first obtain a general sense of the corpus, the top 32 topics were captured as shown above (Fig. 3). Topic 30 reads exactly as we might expect when operating within the realm of social contract theory, but Topic 3 was somewhat surprising, seeming to consider the epistemological system with a discussion of 'mind' and 'ideas' (this, it would seem, is the latent aspect of LDA).

More central to our question, however, is the representation of topics amongs authors.

Here we see an interesting correlation between the topics of interest for Rousseau and Hobbes (Fig. 4, Fig. 6). Specifically, topics 30 and 28 seem of importance to both Hobbes and Rousseau, and these topics seem to involve theories of governance, law, and power. In contrast, the overwhelming subject of interest for Locke appears to be nature, religion and systems of knowledge.

Sentiment Analysis¶

Sentiment analysis was performed using the NRC Sentiment Analysis Lexicon, which is best suited to modern English; the insights obtained were nevertheless instructive.

Briefly returning to Fig. 2, it appears that Locke's Discourses on Humane Understanding may be the root of his marked divergence from Hobbes and Rousseau. It was subsequently helpful to examine sentiment on a text-by-text basis. Looking below (Fig. 9), it almost appears that Hobbes, not Locke, is the writer seeking to distance himself from the field. Unsurprisingly, Leviathan scores the highest out of all works in the 'fear' category. It is also notable that only two works possess negative values for sentiment: one by Locke and one by Rousseau.

Figure 9: sentiment analysis by text.

Moving then, to a more holistic view of sentiment, we probe the more general valence of Hobbes, Rousseau and Locke's works. Locke and Hobbes' dominating sentiment is trust (Figures 10, 12) while Rousseau's works prove more balanced. Locke scores the lowest in terms of fear, but ultimately the three theorists are relatively similar across sentiments.

V. Interpretation¶

Taken in sum, the results of this textual exploration seem partially at odds with centuries of scholarship. The various metrics discussed point to a more complicated dynamic than is commonly represented between Locke, Hobbes and Rousseau, particularly when it comes to the position of Locke. Few would deny the sharp contrast between Hobbes and Rousseau, but Locke sits somewhere between. Based on this investigation, it seems prudent to drop the Hobbes and Locke versus Rousseau dichotomy, instead recognizing that each theorist endeavored to bring a unique perspective to the table.

Now, it must be mentioned that this corpus could certainly be expanded, particularly in the case of Hobbes. Re-running these analyses with some lesser-known (and harder to find) texts might illuminate new avenues of inquiry. Potential future work could include more contemporary responses to social contract theory (thinkers like Kant, Rawls and Pettit), cataloging the evolution of our conception of humankind and the social world that binds us.
